The '''79th Academy Awards''' ceremony, presented by the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] (AMPAS), honored the best [[2006 in film|films of 2006]] and took place February 25, 2007, at the [[Kodak Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]] beginning at 5:30 p.m. [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]] / 8:30 p.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]. During the ceremony, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences presented Academy Awards (commonly referred to as Oscars) in 24 categories. The ceremony, televised in the United States by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], was produced by [[Laura Ziskin]] and directed by Louis J. Horvitz. Actress [[Ellen DeGeneres]] hosted for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ellen, meet Oscar|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/movieawards/oscars/2006-09-07-degeneres-host_x.htm|accessdate=February 16, 2014|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=September 7, 2008}}</ref> Two weeks earlier in a ceremony at the [[Beverly Wilshire Hotel]] in [[Beverly Hills, California]] held on February 10, the [[Academy Award for Technical Achievement|Academy Awards for Technical Achievement]] were presented by host [[Maggie Gyllenhaal]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Rich|first=Joshua|title=Maggie G. Hosts Sci/Tech Oscars|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2007/02/07/maggie_g_hosts_/|accessdate=July 18, 2013|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Inc.|date=February 7, 2007}}</ref>

''[[The Departed]]'' won four awards, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for [[Martin Scorsese]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Halbfinger|first=David M.|last2=Waxman|first2=Sharon|title='The Departed' Wins Best Picture, Scorsese Best Director|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/26/movies/awardsseason/26osca.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=February 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=At Long Last, Scorsese Wins Oscar|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-207_162-2511891.html|accessdate=October 22, 2013|work=[[CBS News]]|publisher=[[CBS Corporation]]|date=February 11, 2009}}</ref>  Other winners included ''[[Pan's Labyrinth]]'' with three, ''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]'', ''[[Dreamgirls (film)|Dreamgirls]]'', and ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'' with two, and ''[[Babel (film)|Babel]]'', ''[[The Blood of Yingzhou District]]'', ''[[The Danish Poet]]'', ''[[Happy Feet]]'', ''[[The Last King of Scotland (film)|The Last King of Scotland]]'', ''[[Letters from Iwo Jima]]'', ''[[The Lives of Others]]'', ''[[Marie Antoinette (2006 film)|Marie Antoinette]]'', ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest]]'', ''[[The Queen (film)|The Queen]]'', and ''[[West Bank Story]]'' with one. The telecast garnered nearly 40 million viewers in the United States.

==Winners and nominees==
<!-- Please do not add any fact or statement below unless you have a credible source verifying it. Otherwise, it will be promptly removed. -->

The nominees for the 79th Academy Awards were announced on January 23, 2007, at the [[Samuel Goldwyn Theater]] in [[Beverly Hills, California]], by [[Sid Ganis]], president of the Academy, and the actress [[Salma Hayek]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Ruthe|title=Sure, the film business is cutthroat, but it also has heart, says industry leader Sid Ganis, who seems to have a lot of heart himself|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Sure-the-film-business-is-cutthroat-but-it-also-2655088.php|accessdate=July 16, 2013|work=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|date=January 22, 2007}}</ref> ''[[Dreamgirls (film)|Dreamgirls]]'' received the most nominations with eight, and ''[[Babel (film)|Babel]]'' came in second with seven.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title='Dreamgirls' Leads Oscar Noms — Without Best Picture Or Beyonce|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1550536/best-picture-snub-oscar-leader-dreamgirls.jhtml|accessdate=February 14, 2014|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom Media Networks]]|date=January 23, 2007}}</ref> This marked the first and only occurrence that the film with the most nominations was not a Best Picture nominee.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rea|first=Steven|title=Oscar hugs and shrugs The Academy Award nominations show unusual diversity this year and, in the case of "Dreamgirls," an oddity. Oscar is doing his part for diversity|url=http://articles.philly.com/2007-01-24/news/25220650_1_time-in-oscar-history-directors-guild-nominations-fourth-best-picture-nomination|accessdate=January 22, 2014|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]]|date=January 24, 2007}}</ref>

The winners were announced during the awards ceremony on February 25, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title='The Departed' Takes Home Best Picture Oscar, Director Award for Martin Scorsese|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2007/02/26/departed-takes-home-best-picture-oscar-director-award-for-martin-scorsese/|date=February 26, 2007|accessdate=September 16, 2011|work=[[Fox News]]|publisher=[[21st Century Fox]]}}</ref> With his latest unsuccessful nomination for Best Actor, [[Peter O'Toole]] became the most nominated performer without a competitive win.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peter O'Toole|url=http://archive.indystar.com/usatoday/article/4031975|accessdate=January 31, 2014|work=[[The Indianapolis Star]]|publisher=Gannett Company|date=December 15, 2013}}</ref> Best Supporting Actress winner [[Jennifer Hudson]] was the fifteenth Oscar acting winner to win for a debut film performance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Montgomery|first=Daniel|title=Will Lupita Nyongo and Barkhad Abdi join 15 Oscar winners for film debuts?|url=http://www.goldderby.com/news/5519/oscars-lupita-nyongo-12-years-a-slave-barkhad-abdi-captain-phillips-news-93526841.html|accessdate=January 31, 2014|work=Gold Derby|date=January 24, 2014}}</ref> "[[I Need to Wake Up]]" from ''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]'' became the first song from a documentary film to win Best Original Song.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 79th Academy Awards (2007) Memorable Moments|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2007/memorable-moments|accessdate=February 14, 2014|work=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|publisher=AMPAS}}</ref>

