==Ceremony information==
[[File:Ellen DeGeneres 2011.jpg|130|thumbnail|right|[[Ellen DeGeneres]] hosted the 79th Academy Awards|alt=Headshot of a blond haired female in her early fifties wearing a blue jacket over blue and white shirts.]]

Because of the declining viewership of recent Academy Awards ceremonies, the Academy sought ideas to revamp the show while renewing interest with the nominated films. In September 2006, the Academy selected producer [[Laura Ziskin]] to oversee production of the telecast for a second time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Archerd|first=Army|title=Oscar gig for Ziskin|url=http://variety.com/2006/film/news/oscar-gig-for-ziskin-1200339437/|accessdate=February 3, 2014|work=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=July 20, 2006}}</ref> Nearly three months later, actress and comedienne [[Ellen DeGeneres]], who had previously emceed three [[Primetime Emmy Award]] ceremonies between 2001 and 2005, was chosen as host of the 2007 ceremony.<ref name="CBS News"/> In an article published in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', Ziskin explained the decision to hire DeGeneres saying "Certainly, I believe the presence of Ellen will help the ratings absolutely. She's popular with a very wide audience. She is not a niche performer. She touches a lot of demographics."<ref>{{cite news|last=Welkos|first=Robert W.|title=Everybody likes Ellen, especially Oscar|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/sep/09/entertainment/et-ellen9|accessdate=February 3, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=September 9, 2006}}</ref>

AMPAS christened this year's telecast with a theme celebrating movie quotes.<ref name="Quotes">{{cite news|title=Movie Quotes Line the Road to Oscars|url=http://oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2007/07.01.25.html|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|publisher=AMPAS|date=January 25, 2007|archiveurl=//web.archive.org/web/20070420220205/http://oscars.org/press/pressreleases/2007/07.01.25.html|archivedate=April 20, 2007}}</ref> In tandem with the theme, advertising agency [[TBWA\Chiat\Day]] designed the official ceremony poster featuring 75 quotes from several Oscar-nominated or winning films.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Oscar poster lines 'em up|url=http://variety.com/2006/film/news/oscar-poster-lines-em-up-1117956079/|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=December 19, 2006}}</ref>  To stir interest surrounding the awards, filmmaker [[Spike Lee]] released a trailer featuring everyday people around [[New York City]] reciting famous film lines.<ref name="Quotes"/> During the ceremony, a montage produced by director [[Nancy Meyers]] saluted the work of screenwriters and their contributions to film.<ref>{{cite news|last=White|first=Dave|title=Oscars: Even more bloated than 'Idol'|url=http://www.today.com/id/17333639/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/oscars-even-more-bloated-idol/|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=[[NBC News]]|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|date=February 26, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Fernandez|first=Jay A.|title=A step toward recognizing where it starts|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/feb/28/entertainment/et-scriptland28|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=February 28, 2007}}</ref>

During the telecast, former [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] and environmental activist [[Al Gore]], and Best Actor nominee [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] announced that AMPAS would incorporate several environmentally and ecologically conscious features into the ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|title=Natural Resources Defense Council "Greens" the Academy Awards|url=http://www.nrdc.org/media/2007/070225.asp|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=[[Natural Resources Defense Council]]|publisher=NDRC|date=February 25, 2007}}</ref> Designed by Frank Webb and Matthew White, the ''[[Architectural Digest]]'' greenroom where presenters and winners mingled backstage featured several environmentally friendly features such as a rug made of recycled plastic bottles and walls painted without any [[volatile organic compounds]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Puente|first=Maria|title=It's stylish, it's lavish, it's&nbsp;... the greenroom?|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/movieawards/oscars/2007-02-14-oscar-greenroom_x.htm|accessdate=February 2014|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=February 14, 2007}}</ref> Other eco-friendly features included the  transportation for guests of the awards via [[hybrid electric vehicle]]s, usage of recyclable paper for ballots and invitations, and serving meals at the Governor's Ball on reusable plates and biodegradable dishware.<ref>{{cite news|last=Faber|first=Judy|title=No Statue, But A Win Nonetheless For Gore|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/no-statue-but-a-win-nonetheless-for-gore/|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=CBS News|publisher=CBS Corporation|date=February 26, 2007}}</ref>

Several other people participated in the production of the ceremony. [[William Ross (composer)|William Ross]] served as musical director for the ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Black, Keaton added to Oscars|url=http://variety.com/2007/film/news/black-keaton-added-to-oscars-1117959866/|accessdate=February 1, 2014|work=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=February 20, 2007}}</ref> [[J. Michael Riva]] designed a new set and stage design for the ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|last=Repstad|first=Laura|title=Riva tapped as production designer|url=http://variety.com/2006/film/news/riva-tapped-as-production-designer-1117956397/|accessdate=February 1, 2014|work=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=December 28, 2006}}</ref> Voice actor [[Don LaFontaine]] was hired with [[Gina Tuttle]] as announcers for the telecast.<ref>{{harvnb|Terrance|2013|p=14}}</ref> Actor [[Greg Vaughan]] and ''[[Lucky (magazine)|Lucky]]'' columnist Allyson Waterman co-hosted "Road to the Oscars", a weekly behind-the-scenes video blog on the Oscar ceremony website.<ref name="Allyson"/> Members of the dance troupe and contortionist group [[Pilobolus (dance company)|Pilobolus]] performed interpretive shadow figures representing scenes and logos from the nominated films.<ref>{{cite news|last=Keck|first=William|title=A star is born in shape- shifting Pilobolus|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/movieawards/oscars/2007-02-22-pilobolus_x.htm|accessdate=February 3, 2014|work=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=February 22, 2007}}</ref> Actors [[Jack Black]], [[Will Ferrell]], and [[John C. Reilly]] performed a lighthearted musical number written by comedic director [[Judd Apatow]] and music composer [[Marc Shaiman]] satirizing comedy's lack of recognition at the Academy Awards.<ref>{{cite news|last=Apatow|first=Judd|title=Apatow recalls working with Shaiman|url=http://variety.com/2007/film/news/apatow-recalls-working-with-shaiman-1117968231/|accessdate=February 17, 2014|work=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=July 9, 2007}}</ref> Conducted by musician [[Steve Sidwell (musician)|Steve Sidwell]], the [[Sound Effects Choir]] performed voice effects to a montage of classic films.<ref>{{cite web|title=Composer {{!}} Steve Sidwell|url=http://www.unippmglobal.com/#/composers/Composers%20Q-Z/Barnaby%20Taylor.aspx|work=[[Universal Music Publishing Group]]|publisher=NBCUniversal|accessdate=February 3, 2014}}</ref> Another vignette directed by documentary fimmaker [[Errol Morris]] featuring several Oscar nominees discussing what it means to be an Oscar nominee was shown at the beginning of the show.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Anne|title=Morris cuts it close with his Oscar docu|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/morris-cuts-close-his-oscar-130781|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=February 23, 2007|page=6}}</ref> Italian director [[Giuseppe Tornatore]] assembled a tribute highlighting previous winners of the [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Susman|first=Gary|title=Oscars '07: 10 Memorable Moments|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20009747_20013925,00.html|accessdate=February 14, 2014|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Inc.|date=February 27, 2007}}</ref> Filmmaker [[Michael Mann (director)|Michael Mann]] produced a montage highlighting American life through the eyes of cinema.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Lisa|title=An icon gets his due, but not for best work|url=http://www.denverpost.com/colleges/ci_5305931?source=pkg|accessdate=February 14, 2014|work=[[The Denver Post]]|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=February 26, 2007}}</ref>

===Box office performance of nominated films===
At the time of the nominations announcement on January 23, the combined gross of the five Best Picture nominees was $244&nbsp;million with an average of $48.7&nbsp;million per film.<ref name="BoxOfficeMojoOscars">{{cite news|title=2006 Academy Award Nominations and Winner for Best Picture|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/oscar/chart/?yr=2006&p=.htm|accessdate=January 30, 2014|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]}}</ref> ''The Departed'' was the highest earner among the Best Picture nominees with $121.7 million in domestic box office receipts. The film was followed by ''Little Miss Sunshine'' ($59.6 million), ''The Queen'' ($35.6 million), ''Babel'' ($23.7 million), and finally ''Letters from Iwo Jima'' ($2.4 million).<ref name=BoxOfficeMojoOscars />

Of the top 50 grossing movies of the year, 29 nominations went to nine films on the list. Only ''The Pursuit of Happyness'' (12th), ''Borat: Cultural Learnings of America for Make Benefit Glorious Nation of Kazakhstan'' (15th), ''The Devil Wears Prada'' (16th), ''The Departed'' (17th), and ''Dreamgirls'' (28th) were nominated for Best Picture, Best Animated Feature, or any of the directing, acting, or screenwriting awards.<ref name="boxofficemojooscars">{{cite news|title=2007 Domestic Grosses (as of January 23, 2007)|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?asof=2007-01-23&view=releasedate&view2=domestic&yr=2006&sort=gross&order=DESC&p=.htm|accessdate=April 16, 2007|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> The other top 50 box office hits that earned nominations were ''Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Man's Chest'' (1st), ''Cars'' (2nd), ''Superman Returns'' (6th), and ''Happy Feet'' (8th).<ref name="boxofficemojooscars"/>

===Critical reviews===
The show received a mixed reception from media publications. Some media outlets were more critical of the show. Tim Goodman of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' lamented, "It was long. It was flat. And it was bloated. Worst of all, it was boring." He also wrote that "it was difficult for Ellen's subtle rambling to translate because people want pop and humor and declarative sentences in their Academy Awards. Which they didn't exactly get."<ref>{{cite news|last=Goodman|first=Tim|title=Departed evening of bloated, boring Hollywood babble|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/THE-79TH-ACADEMY-AWARDS-Departed-evening-of-2646004.php|accessdate=February 6, 2014|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]]|date=February 25, 2007}}</ref> ''[[The Denver Post]]'' television critic Joanne Ostrow bemoaned, "Pleasant and innocuous but hardly exciting, DeGeneres forgot the primary Academy Award host directive: It's not about the host. Hollywood's biggest night (and television's second-biggest annual gathering, after the [[Super Bowl]]) is a celebration of film."<ref>{{cite news|last=Ostrow|first=Joanne|title=Mediocre Ellen lowers telecast to daytime|url=http://www.denverpost.com/opinion/ci_5305942|accessdate=February 6, 2014|work=The Denver Post|publisher=MediaNews Group|date=February 26, 2007}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' columnist [[Tom Shales]] gave an average review for DeGeneres but criticized the overall slow and choppy pacing of the program noting that it was "punishingly too long."<ref>{{cite news|last=Shales|first=Tom|title=The Broadcast: Long and Longer|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/26/AR2007022600027.html|accessdate=February 6, 2014|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]]|date=February 26, 2007}}</ref>

Other media outlets received the broadcast more positively. Columnist [[Alessandra Stanley]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' lauded DeGeneres's performance writing that she was "cheeky but good-natured, far less barbed and sardonic than [[Jon Stewart]] [[78th Academy Awards|last year]] or [[Chris Rock]] in [[77th Academy Awards|2005]]." She added that her style brought a "casual Friday mood to Fancy Sunday."<ref>{{cite news|last=Stanley|first=Alessandra|title=Bringing a Touch of Daytime to Hollywood's Biggest Night|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/26/arts/television/26watc.html?_r=0|accessdate=February 3, 2014|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=February 25, 2007}}</ref> ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' television critic Gail Pennington praised host DeGeneres and producer Ziskin for turning "the evening into an upbeat celebration&ndash;–and the most entertaining Oscars in years."<ref>{{cite news|last=Pennington|first=Gail|title=DeGeneres kept the Oscar show upbeat and lively|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|publisher=[[Lee Enterprises]]|date=February 26, 2007|page=D1}}</ref> Television editor Dave Kronke of the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' gave high marks for DeGeneres commenting, "Her material was amusing but scarcely a laugh riot, yet it was amiable and delineated that the evening was a celebration of all the nominees, not just the winners."<ref>{{cite news|last=Kronke|first=David|title=Yep, She's Funny Gentle Humor wins for DeGeneres|work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|publisher=MediaNews Group|date=February 26, 2007|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/YEP,+SHE%27S+FUNNY+GENTLE+HUMOR+WINS+FOR+DEGENERES.-a0159975212}}</ref>

===Ratings and reception===
The American telecast on ABC drew in an average of 39.92 million people over its length, which was a 2.5% increase from the previous year's ceremony.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Bill|last=Gorman | title=Academy Awards Averages 41.3 Million Viewers; Most Since 2005 |url=http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/03/08/academy-awards-averages-41-3-million-viewers-most-since-2005/44217 | publisher=TVbytheNumbers | date=March 8, 2010| accessdate=March 12, 2010| archiveurl= //web.archive.org/web/20100310080531/http://tvbythenumbers.com/2010/03/08/academy-awards-averages-41-3-million-viewers-most-since-2005/44217| archivedate= 10 March 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rich|first=Joshua|title=A few lingering Oscar curiosities|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2007/02/27/a_few_lingering/|accessdate=January 31, 2014|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Inc.|date=February 27, 2007}}</ref> An estimated 76.72 million total viewers watched all or part of the awards.<ref name="Nikki Finke Oscar ratings"/> The show also drew higher [[Nielsen ratings]] compared to the previous ceremony with 23.59% of households watching over a 38.86 share.<ref name="TVB Oscars">{{cite news|title=Academy Awards ratings|work=[[Television Bureau of Advertising]]|format=PDF|url=http://www.tvb.org/media/file/Academy_Awards.pdf|accessdate=June 27, 2013}}</ref> In addition, the program scored a higher 18-49 demo rating with a 14.18 rating over a 33.71 share among viewers in that demographic.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gough|first=Paul J.|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/strong-week-abc-but-idol-131032|title=Strong week for ABC, but 'Idol' lifts Fox|accessdate=January 31, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=February 28, 2007}}</ref>

In July 2007, the ceremony presentation received nine nominations at the [[59th Primetime Emmy Awards|59th Primetime Emmys]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Primetime Emmy Award Database|url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/79th-annual-academy-awards|accessdate=July 18, 2013|work=[[Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]]|publisher=ATAS}}</ref> Two months later, the ceremony won two of those nominations for Outstanding Art Direction (J. Michael Riva, Geoffrey Richman, and Tamlyn Wright) and Outstanding Music Direction (William Ross).<ref>{{cite news|title=Emmy Winners List|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/emmy-winners-list/|accessdate=July 17, 2013|work=CBS News|publisher=CBS Corporation|date=September 16, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The complete list of winners|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/sep/17/entertainment/et-emmywinners17|accessdate=February 1, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=Tribune Publishing|date=September 17, 2007}}</ref>

